      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_4.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Canyon Visitor Education Center">
      <data key="d0">IMG_ENTITY</data>
      <data key="d1">The image captures an interactive exhibit within an indoor public setting, featuring a child engaging with a spherical fountain. This directly corresponds to the 'Canyon Visitor Education Center,' which the text describes as a place for visitors to 'see, hear, and learn' about Yellowstone's supervolcano, geysers, hot springs, and geologic history, implying such educational and interactive displays. The text also explicitly refers to an image of this center with '(shown below)', further confirming the match.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_4.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMAGE_3&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ORI_IMG"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The image is a black and white photograph depicting a grand and powerful waterfall cascading down a rugged, mountainous landscape. Dominating the center of the frame, the waterfall appears as a bright, frothy torrent of water, plunging from a high cliff face into a misty pool below. The force of the water creates a visible spray at its base, contributing to the ethereal quality of the scene in grayscale. The waterfall is flanked by steep, heavily forested slopes. On the right side, a prominent, jagged rock formation with distinct vertical striations rises sharply, providing a dramatic contrast to the smooth flow of the water. On the left, dense coniferous trees cling to the rocky terrain, extending upwards and receding into the background, hinting at a vast wilderness. At the very bottom of the gorge, partially obscured by the mist and surrounding foliage, a winding river or stream can be faintly discerned. The overall perspective suggests the photograph was taken from a high vantage point, looking down into the deep canyon. The grayscale palette enhances the dramatic contrast between the bright, dynamic water and the dark, textured rocks and dense foliage, conveying a sense of immense natural power and untamed beauty."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_3.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Yellowstone River Waterfall&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">A large, powerful cascade of water falling from a significant height within the Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone, appearing bright white in the grayscale image due to its rapid movement. This includes the notable Upper and Lower Falls of the Yellowstone River, a key highlight of Yellowstone National Park.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_3.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">A spectacular, deep, narrow valley with steep, rugged sides, formed by geological erosion, encompassing the Yellowstone River waterfalls and the surrounding landscape. This prominent feature of Yellowstone National Park can be viewed from overlooks and trails in the Canyon Village area, as well as from Tower Fall and Calcite Springs overlooks. Climbing in the Grand Canyon is illegal due to loose, crumbly rock.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_3.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Canyon Cliffs&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">Steep, dark rock formations that form the rugged sides of the Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone, framing the waterfall and showing vertical textures. These geological features contribute to the spectacular scenery of Yellowstone National Park, though climbing on them is generally not recommended due to safety concerns like loose rock.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_3.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Yellowstone Forest&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">Dense, dark evergreen trees covering the slopes and tops of the cliffs and hills within the canyon, indicating a wild, natural environment characteristic of Yellowstone National Park. These forested areas provide crucial habitat for a variety of wildlife, including large mammals like grizzly and black bears, wolves, elk, and bison, which are abundant in the park.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_3.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Yellowstone River&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">A significant body of water flowing at the base of the waterfalls and winding through the Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone, continuing the flow of the cascade downstream. This river is a central feature of Yellowstone National Park, creating the iconic Upper and Lower Falls, and is distinct from other park rivers like the Lewis River where non-motorized boating is permitted.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_3.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Lower Falls of the Yellowstone River">
      <data key="d0">IMG_ENTITY</data>
      <data key="d1">The image is a black and white photograph showcasing a grand and powerful waterfall, which is identified in the text as the Lower Falls of the Yellowstone River, a spectacular highlight within the Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone National Park.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_3.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMAGE_2&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ORI_IMG"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The image is a black and white photograph capturing an intense moment between two large elk, likely engaged in a sparring match or a dominance display. Both elk are depicted in profile, with their heads lowered and antlers intricately locked together at the center of the frame. The elk on the left is positioned with its body facing towards the left edge of the image and its head turned sharply to the right, engaging with the other elk. Its dark, muscular neck and shoulder are visible. The elk on the right is positioned with its body facing towards the right edge of the image, and its head turned towards the left, meeting the other animal. Both animals possess impressive, multi-tined antlers that appear strong and robust as they intertwine. The fur of both elk appears dark and textured due to the black and white rendering. The background is softly blurred, providing a shallow depth of field that keeps the focus sharply on the two animals and their interaction. The blurred background suggests a natural outdoor environment, possibly a grassy or rocky terrain, but it is indistinct enough not to distract from the main subjects. The overall atmosphere of the image is one of raw power, natural instinct, and dynamic confrontation."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_2.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Left Bull Elk&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">A large, dark-furred male elk (bull) viewed from its left side, with its head lowered. Its prominent, multi-tined antlers are engaged in a struggle with another elk, a behavior explicitly referred to as 'sparring' in the context of Yellowstone National Park wildlife. The elk appears to be in motion, possibly pushing or grappling. Visitors to Yellowstone are reminded to maintain a safe distance of at least 25 yards (23m) from elk and other animals.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_2.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Right Bull Elk&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">A large, dark-furred male elk (bull) viewed from its front-right, with its head lowered. Its prominent, multi-tined antlers are engaged in a struggle with another elk, a scene captured in Yellowstone National Park as 'bull elk sparring.' The elk appears to be bracing itself or pushing back. The park guidelines emphasize keeping a safe distance of at least 25 yards (23m) from all animals, including elk.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_2.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Left Bull Elk's Antlers&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"OBJECT"</data>
      <data key="d1">Large, dark, multi-tined antlers belonging to the left bull elk. They are actively interlocked with the antlers of the right elk, forming the central point of their confrontation. This interlocked state is typical of 'sparring' behavior among bull elk, a common sight in areas like Yellowstone National Park.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_2.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Right Bull Elk's Antlers&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"OBJECT"</data>
      <data key="d1">Large, dark, multi-tined antlers belonging to the right bull elk. They are actively interlocked with the antlers of the left elk, forming the central point of their confrontation. This engagement is a key aspect of 'bull elk sparring,' a behavior noted in the wildlife of Yellowstone National Park.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_2.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;Yellowstone National Park Terrain&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">A blurry, natural outdoor environment, likely consisting of grassy ground or low vegetation, indicating a wild habitat. This terrain is characteristic of Yellowstone National Park, a high-altitude area (most of the park is above 7,500 feet) known for its unpredictable weather and diverse wildlife. The background is out of focus, emphasizing the elk in the foreground, which are part of the abundant mammal population in the park.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_2.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A national park located in Wyoming that requires reservations for certain group sizes and RV campsites. It is also the location for contact addresses of Xanterra Parks and Resorts and the National Park Service."&lt;SEP&gt;"Yellowstone National Park is a federal recreation site where entrance fees are charged, offering various pass options, camping facilities, and subject to seasonal weather changes and visitor access reviews."&lt;SEP&gt;"Yellowstone National Park is a major national park in the US, providing various services and subject to specific road schedules and closures."&lt;SEP&gt;"Yellowstone National Park is a national park with specific regulations for visitors, including fishing, boating, and camping."&lt;SEP&gt;"Yellowstone National Park is an organization and a geographic location, providing visitor information, activities, and road schedules. It is the first national park in America."&lt;SEP&gt;"Yellowstone National Park is the primary location described in the trip planner, known for its high altitude, unpredictable weather, busy roads, dangerous hydrothermal features, and diverse wildlife."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-47639910c915bafe8d80a13752ccb8ee&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2b3cdc79954b41510d5ae0999ef6daf3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c35ba44e693c85e6206ade502e115d5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-88e5c2ce20f231e3a806b09b6cab2c4d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e22ff6904de7a8eef70b8467d191a104&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7351b12b3e5ac87b530aa3bf02ecf8cc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMAGE_1&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ORI_IMG"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The image captures a breathtaking natural landscape featuring an erupting geyser under a clear blue sky, highlighted by a vibrant rainbow. In the central foreground, a large geyser vigorously erupts, sending a towering column of dense, white steam and water vapor high into the air. The steam plume is thick and billows upwards, then spreads out and drifts towards the right side of the frame, forming a soft, cloud-like mass against the sky. The geyser emerges from a textured, light grey to off-white mineral formation, which appears rocky and uneven, indicative of geothermal deposits. The ground immediately surrounding the geyser is also a light, earthy tone, with scattered rocks and what appears to be wet or reflective patches, suggesting pools of water or damp soil. Arched gracefully through the rising steam and against the bright blue sky is a prominent and vivid rainbow. Its full spectrum of colors—red, orange, yellow, green, blue, and violet—is clearly visible, creating a striking contrast with the white steam and blue sky. The rainbow originates near the base of the steam column on the left and extends downwards towards the right, seemingly touching the distant tree line. In the mid-ground, a dense forest of dark green coniferous trees stretches across the horizon, forming a natural backdrop behind the geyser and the rainbow. The trees are tall and appear to be evergreen, providing a rich, dark contrast to the lighter elements of the geyser and sky. The sky itself is a brilliant, unblemished blue, with only faint, wispy clouds present, primarily interacting with the geyser's steam. The overall atmosphere of the image is one of natural wonder, power, and serene beauty, showcasing a unique and awe-inspiring moment where geothermal activity meets atmospheric optics."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_1.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GEYSER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A natural hot spring that periodically erupts, ejecting a powerful column of hot water and steam. It forms a prominent, light-colored, rocky cone-like structure in the foreground."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_1.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STEAM PLUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"OBJECT"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A thick, towering column of white vapor vigorously erupting from the geyser, rising high into the blue sky and dispersing into clouds."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_1.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RAINBOW&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"OBJECT"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A vibrant, multi-colored arc of light visible through or within the steam plume, extending from near the ground to higher in the sky."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_1.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SKY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A clear and bright blue sky, forming the upper background of the scene, with some faint white clouds formed by the dispersing steam."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_1.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FOREST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A dense line of dark green evergreen trees covering a distant ridge, forming the natural backdrop behind the geyser and extending across the middle ground."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_1.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BARREN GROUND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The light-colored, uneven, and rocky terrain immediately surrounding the geyser, appearing wet or mineral-rich from geothermic activity."</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_1.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="Geysers &amp; Hot Springs">
      <data key="d0">IMG_ENTITY</data>
      <data key="d1">This textual entity describes the geothermal features of Yellowstone National Park, including geysers, hot springs, mudpots, and fumaroles, which are evidence of volcanic activity. The image perfectly illustrates this with a prominent erupting geyser under a rainbow, showcasing the natural wonder described.</data>
      <data key="d2">test_runs/test_mmrag_working\images\image_1.jpg</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAMMOTH HOT SPRINGS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Mammoth Hot Springs is a specific location in Yellowstone National Park known for its hot springs and other hydrothermal features."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-8f0e2c09fcd8882a570819d4a5395ca3</data>
    </node>
